  "text": "The Kubernetes controller work queue with rate limiting is implemented in the client-go library and used throughout the Kubernetes controller manager. The core implementation resides in staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/util/workqueue/.\n\n## Core Components\n\n### Queue Interfaces and Implementations\n\n1. **Basic Queue (queue.go)**: The TypedInterface interface and Typed struct define the fundamental queue operations with methods Add(item T), Get() (item T, shutdown bool), Done(item T), Len(), ShutDown(), ShutDownWithDrain(), and ShuttingDown(). The implementation uses internal dirty and processing sets to track item states, ensuring items are processed exactly once and can be re-added if marked dirty during processing.\n\n2. **Delaying Queue (delaying_queue.go)**: The TypedDelayingInterface extends TypedInterface with the AddAfter(item T, duration time.Duration) method, enabling delayed re-enqueueing. The internal Typed struct manages a heap-based waitingFor queue to delay items until ready.\n\n3. **Rate Limiting Queue (rate_limiting_queue.go)**: The TypedRateLimitingInterface extends TypedDelayingInterface with rate-limited re-enqueueing: AddRateLimited(item T), Forget(item T), and NumRequeues(item T) int. The internal rateLimitingType struct wraps a TypedDelayingInterface and TypedRateLimiter. RateLimitingInterface is the deprecated non-generic type alias.\n\n### Rate Limiters (default_rate_limiters.go)\n\n1. **TypedRateLimiter[T comparable]**: Core interface with methods When(item T) time.Duration, Forget(item T), and NumRequeues(item T) int. RateLimiter is the deprecated non-generic alias.\n\n2. **ItemExponentialFailureRateLimiter / TypedItemExponentialFailureRateLimiter[T]**: Implements exponential backoff with the formula baseDelay * 2^(num-failures), capped at maxDelay. The When() method computes backoff using fast-path overflow checking. NumRequeues() returns the failure count for an item. Forget() clears the failure count when an item succeeds. Created with NewItemExponentialFailureRateLimiter(baseDelay, maxDelay) or NewTypedItemExponentialFailureRateLimiter[T](baseDelay, maxDelay).\n\n3. **BucketRateLimiter / TypedBucketRateLimiter[T]**: Adapts golang.org/x/time/rate.Limiter (token bucket algorithm) to the workqueue API. The When() method reserves a token and returns the delay. NumRequeues() always returns 0 (no per-item tracking). Forget() is a no-op. Provides global rate limiting across all items.\n\n4. **DefaultControllerRateLimiter / DefaultTypedControllerRateLimiter[T]()**: Factory function creating a TypedMaxOfRateLimiter that combines ItemExponentialFailureRateLimiter (5ms base, 1000s max) and BucketRateLimiter (10 qps, 100 bucket). Returns the maximum delay from both limiters, providing both per-item exponential backoff and overall rate limiting.\n\n5. **TypedMaxOfRateLimiter[T]**: Combines multiple TypedRateLimiter instances, returning the maximum When() delay and maximum NumRequeues() value. Calls Forget() on all constituent limiters.\n\n## Controller Reconcile Loop Pattern\n\nControllers implement the standard reconcile loop using three core queue operations:\n\n### Example: staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/examples/workqueue/main.go\nThe canonical example demonstrates the complete pattern in Controller.processNextItem():\n- queue.Get() blocks until work is available, returning a key and shutdown flag\n- Deferred queue.Done(key) marks work completion\n- Calls sync function (syncToStdout) with business logic\n- Controller.handleErr() implements retry logic: queue.Forget(key) on success or after NumRequeues() >= 5, otherwise queue.AddRateLimited(key) to requeue with rate limiting\n- Controller.Run() spawns worker goroutines calling runWorker() which loops on processNextItem()\n\n### Production Controllers\n\n1. **pkg/controller/deployment/deployment_controller.go**: DeploymentController uses TypedRateLimitingInterface[string] queue field. The processNextWorkItem() method (lines 487-498) implements the core pattern: queue.Get() retrieves the next deployment key, deferred queue.Done(key) ensures cleanup, syncHandler() processes the deployment. The handleErr() method (lines 500-520) calls queue.Forget(key) on success or if NumRequeues(key) >= maxRetries (15), otherwise queue.AddRateLimited(key) for exponential backoff retry with (5ms * 2^n) delays.\n\n2. **pkg/controller/bootstrap/tokencleaner.go**: TokenCleaner manages bootstrap token expiration. The processNextWorkItem() method (lines 145-160) follows the pattern: queue.Get() retrieves the next secret key, deferred queue.Done(key), syncFunc() checks and removes expired tokens. On error, queue.AddRateLimited() requeues; on success, queue.Forget() clears tracking.\n\n3. **pkg/controller/bootstrap/bootstrapsigner.go**: BootstrapSigner processes bootstrap CSR signing requests. Uses the queue in its syncLoop() with queue.Get() and queue.Done() pattern.\n\n## Design Benefits\n\nThe work queue design ensures:\n- **Fair distribution**: FIFO ordering with per-worker processing\n- **Reliability**: Deferred Done() ensures items aren't lost even if a worker crashes\n- **Exponential backoff**: Failed items experience increasingly long delays (5ms, 10ms, 20ms, 40ms, ..., capped at 1000s)\n- **Overall rate limiting**: Token bucket prevents overwhelming dependent systems (e.g., API server)\n- **Idempotency support**: The same item can be processed multiple times safely, with the cache ensuring consistent state\n- **Production-ready**: Suitable for managing thousands of objects in large Kubernetes clusters"
